{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646892"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:37:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:37:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18215"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18215"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10929"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79351"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10929"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18215"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64673"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25405"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25408"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79351"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBone tissue has distinct microarchitectural arrangements that provide both structural and metabolic functions. The two main types are cortical (compact) and trabecular (spongy) bone.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the structural organisation of bone tissue?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Overlapping parallel osteons in cortical bone limit crack propagation","Trabecular bone lattice aligns opposite to stress direction","Cortical bone performs primary metabolic functions","Trabecular bone has higher density than cortical bone","Cortical bone has greater surface area for remodelling"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOverlapping parallel osteons in cortical bone limit crack propagation\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. Cortical bone contains cylindrical Haversian systems (osteons) that run parallel to the long axis of the bone. Their overlapping arrangement helps prevent crack propagation and provides structural strength.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrabecular bone lattice aligns opposite to stress direction\u003C/strong\u003E - Trabecular bone actually aligns along lines of mechanical stress to provide optimal support while maintaining low weight\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECortical bone performs primary metabolic functions\u003C/strong\u003E - Trabecular bone, not cortical bone, is primarily responsible for metabolic functions due to its greater surface area and vascularity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrabecular bone has higher density than cortical bone\u003C/strong\u003E - Cortical bone is denser than trabecular bone, which has a porous structure\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECortical bone has greater surface area for remodelling\u003C/strong\u003E - The lattice-like structure of trabecular bone provides a much larger surface area for metabolic activity and remodelling\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese structural differences allow bones to maintain strength while minimising weight and supporting metabolic functions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cortical bone contains parallel osteons (Haversian systems) that help resist crack propagation through their overlapping arrangement.","Trabecular (spongy) bone has a lattice structure aligned with stress directions to provide strength while maintaining low weight.","Trabecular bone has greater surface area and metabolic activity compared to cortical bone."],"references":["Khurana, I., Khurana, A., \u0026 Kowlgi, N. G. (2019). Textbook of Medical Physiology_-E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clarke B. Normal bone anatomy and physiology. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2008 Nov;3 Suppl 3(Suppl 3):S131-9. doi: 10.2215/CJN.04151206. PMID: 18988698; PMCID: PMC3152283","Florencio-Silva R, Sasso GR, Sasso-Cerri E, Sim\u00f5es MJ, Cerri PS. Biology of Bone Tissue: Structure, Function, and Factors That Influence Bone Cells. Biomed Res Int. 2015;2015:421746. doi: 10.1155/2015/421746. Epub 2015 Jul 13. PMID: 26247020; PMCID: PMC4515490","Cowan PT, Launico MV, Kahai P. Anatomy, Bones. 2024 Apr 21. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725884"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64673"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18215"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64673"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T10:20:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T10:27:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10929"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79351"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relation